BitFarm was never conceived as a company building greenhouses or developing software. It was created as an attempt to connect two worlds that had existed separately for decades: the world of computing and the world of biological production.
We believed that computation could become as important a resource for agriculture as water, energy, and fertile soil. We believed that data could make plant cultivation more predictable, and that artificial intelligence could help people make more precise decisions. We believed that the origin of every product should be verifiable, and that trust should be confirmed by facts rather than promises.
But above all, we believed that technology must benefit the Earth.
If, twenty years from now, BitFarm produces more output but depletes the soil, consumes more resources, or forces people to choose between profit and responsibility, then we have lost our way.
If, on the other hand, each new production cycle makes the land healthier, reduces water and energy losses, improves product quality, and makes the origin of food transparent, then the original idea has survived.
I hope that by then Proof of Growing has become a global standard of trust, and that people choose products not only by price and appearance, but also because they know exactly how they were grown.
I hope that BitFarm has become an open platform on which thousands of companies create equipment, applications, artificial intelligence models, and new technologies. Because the real goal was never to do everything ourselves. The real goal was to create an ecosystem capable of evolving faster than any single company.
I hope that BitFarm’s collective intelligence has become the company’s most valuable asset. Not buildings, not servers, not capital, and not technologies, but knowledge accumulated through millions of production cycles and accessible to every ecosystem participant.
